### §9.10.1 Root-cause analysis — why Amendments 1/2/3 failed to fix the banner

The persistent iOS banner regression across Amendments 1/2/3 was not caused by SW lifecycle behavior. **The load-bearing bug was a stray `display: flex;` declaration inside the `#update-banner` CSS rule that unconditionally overrode the preceding `display: none;`, making the banner always visible regardless of JavaScript state.**

```diff
 #update-banner {
   display: none;        /* sets initial hidden state */
   ...
   z-index: 9999;
-  display: flex;        /* REMOVED — overrode display:none; banner was always visible */
   align-items: center;
   gap: 12px;
   white-space: nowrap;
 }
-#update-banner.visible { display: flex; }   /* REMOVED — dead code with inline-style pattern */
```

Amendments 1/2/3 were diagnosing and patching SW lifecycle code (`skipWaiting` timing, `reg.update()` double-install, `GET_CACHE_NAME` CACHE_NAME comparison) that was never the root cause. The banner displayed unconditionally on iOS because CSS forced it visible; no SW event needed to trigger it. The two fixes that actually shipped with Amendment 4: (1) the CSS one-liner removal — load-bearing cause; (2) the Spanish IIFE JS port — worthwhile secondary cleanup (reverted 80+ lines of Amendment 1/2/3 complexity, restored Spanish §1.6 parity), but not what fixed the symptom.
